## Constraints
### Time
<!-- Deadline or time window? -->
- This feature must be implemented before adding DDR3 support
- This feature must be ready before developing a memory monitor

### Compatibility
<!-- Compatibility constraints with versions, hardware, etc. -->
- Maintain compatibility by using the latest versions of System Verilog and Verilog
- C23 and C++23 preferred for firmware and simulation.
- The firmware must have conditional compilation to support the UART 16550 used by QEMU or the Verilog UARTRX for Verilator and FPGA

### Hardware/Resource
<!-- Hardware or resource limitations -->
- It must be possible to use it in QEMU for firmware testing, i.e., the QEMU simulation must have the same behavior as in Verilator.
- Consider that it must also work in Verilator for a systemic test, i.e., Verilator must be able to compile and run the simulation
- Prepare for GoWin synthesis: functionalities developed exclusively to support Verilator and QEMU simulations must be correctly delimited by conditional compilation
- use the verilog uart rx module already in the codebase for Verilator/FPGA.
- Currently, UART TX uses one address to write the character, and reading it returns the status. The new functionality should have 3 registers: one for writing the character to the UART, one for reading the RX buffer, and one for the UART status. 
    - Writing to the UART TX register (currently 0x1000_0000) will transmit the character
    - Reading the UART TX register will result in 0x00
    - Writing the (new) UART_RX register will do nothing (discard)
    - Reading the (new) UART_RX register will return the last character available in the RX buffer of the UART
    - A new read-only UART_STATUS register must reflect the RX and TX status bits (received_and_valid, busy, etc...)
- The new registers and bitmap must be proposed by the solution architect.
 
